title: Box cutter blade slide and locking mechanism

description.text:
This is a replica of the sliding and locking mechanism found on some models of box cutters, so you can print a new one if it happens to be broken. The one I made this for, was probably 1000 times cheaper than all the work I spent on modeling this, but I mainly did it to see how well this could work, and it does work extremely well. It certainly is better than the original part.

This is difficult to print because it is tiny and has nasty overhangs, so I provide the models with built-in supports that break away easily. Some cutting or sanding will probably still be required to make everything fit and work smoothly.

This needs to be very strong and springy. ABS and PETG are probably the best choices, PLA might be too brittle and too stiff to work well. A bit of silicone oil/grease on the parts can help to make them slide more smoothly.

I don't know how standard these cutters are, likely there will be variations in tolerances between different brands. You may need to scale the models by one or more percents in the X and/or Y directions to make it work smoothly for your particular cutter.

description.text:
Magnet ring and CDI sensor bracket for doing a electronic ignition conversion (glow or gasoline) of ASP FS400-AR radial engine.

Magnet ring
Designed for 3x1.5mm magnet, and a 2mm bolt and nut to clamp it in place (or use CA). There's a notch, once timing is set and confirmed, make a scratch in the prop hub adapter to make re-timing easier if it shifts.

Sensor bracket
Requires a 8x10 mm (aluminum?) stud, drilled to accept a longer crankcase cover bolt (4x25mm I think?). This is epoxied into the bracket, flush with the bottom, so that the bolt is pushing the crankcase cover closed via the stud, without stressing the plastic bracket.
Cut the mounting arms off the sensor and align the depth with the magnet ring, then hot-glue it into the bracket with the flat side facing the magnets.

description.text:
This is a 28mm version of the Epic scale Sicaran battle tank by Ologhzul (many thanks to him for the original model !) for your WH40K games :)
I added as much details as my skills in 3D modelling and my time allow, and improved the model by adding many pieces borrowed to other makers :

  • the tracks are rescaled from the amazing Ground Plunderer of outofstep
  • the hull heavy bolter is also from the ground plunderer, as well as the targeters for the sponson lasers.
  • the laser side turrets are remixes of the laser turrets of jdteixeira's Albatross.
  • the muzzles are also taken from jdteixeira (man I love your job !!!)
  • the engine unit is mainly a remix from the space troops transport by Typhus94
    Thank you all guys !!

On the pictures, you can see I added spare bits from other WH40K sprues (including the hatch, which is a spare hatch from a GW tank kit). What you may not see is that I made holes and put magnets on several parts (mainly the side turrets) to customize it with other options ;)

EDIT 23 october 2017 : I remade most of the files to regroup them in order to simplify the prints (I groupped all the elements of the side turrets in one file, and added the canon nozzles to the main turret thing). I also remade the tracks sprue in order to be able to print them on bed less than 25 cm wide !

EDIT 11 january 2018 : added file "Sicaran_Assemblage.stl" to show how the parts should be assembled.

NOTE : this model needs some cutting and adjusting to be assembled properly as some pieces are of general purpose for several other objects I use (as for the tracks for example, and some parts are optional or can simply be discarded for this model)

title: Monoprice Ultimate Cooling Duct
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Works with the Monoprice Ultimate and Duplicator 6 stock fan.

I decided to take a different approach to cooling.....I actually removed the shroud entirely! The problem with using typical style ducts in the first place is that no matter how open you make it, even with a blower fan, there's always backdraft on your fan blades, meaning the pressure finds the path of the least resistance, and while one of those paths is your duct hole(s), most of them aren't.

Using any style duct, if you feel behind the fan blades, you can feel this backdraft.
Technically, you can print better than any duct by not using any duct at all! The fan will blow down onto the bed, and then scatter off in all directions. Funny enough, this provides more airflow in the prints direction than any duct ever could, simply because the tight spaces we're trying to squeeze this air through.

The reality is, unless you're compressing air, which fans aren't designed to do, you can never fully push every bit of air through an opening less than the size of the intake.

So instead of trying to best direct the airflow through a series of small holes which inevitably leads to blowback because it's deflecting off of the surface immediately in front of the fan, instead I decided on a better simpler design.

In this design not all of the airflow may be directed at the print or exact point of extrusion, but it is more air than you would get with any duct, and most importantly, it stops the blowback you get that seeps backwards through the fan blades. All the air that gets sucked into the fan blades, gets directed down and to the side toward where the extrusion of plastic happens. The result is most of the air flow goes in the general direction of the print.....much more than the stock duct or any custom duct with holes.

The result is better part cooling and better overhang capabilities with the stock fan.

The original model while absolutely stunning in detail is massively broken in slicers. (its actually a ton of individual parts) I ran it through netfab to "fix" those issues and also stood it on its end.

with a little work you can print this with nearly no support and in 2 pieces.

turn the ship nose down. sink it into the bed in your slicer until the nacelles just BARELY touch the print bed.

see that brim disk I included? drop two of them on the bed FIRST and move them to the side. use one for each nacelle. (otherwise they will break away)

you only need support for the hard overhand between the nacelles and the engineering hull. no infill is needed. just print 4 perimeters.

for the front half point it nose up and again raise/lower till the nacelles just touch the bed (zoom in and use the WINDOW on the side of the hull to get the right location)

you can print this with no support and with no infill SAVE one section. the deflector dish is a pretty much sure failure without support. I added 25% grid support to that section only.

glue the two halves together. done.

I have included 2 sets of gcode. the first set is for my Ender 2 and prints amazingly well and should work on ANY printer with sufficient build volume. this is tested good (its the model in the picture)

the second set of gcode is mega sized for the CR10 specifically. it is UNTESTED but I will be printing it in the next week or so once I get the grey filament in the mail that I want to print it with.

title: The Dramatic Yet Balanced D20 Dice

description.text:
A Dramatic D20 with Personality and Character

This is a D20 dice that I've designed that would be what I considered to be a great dice:

  1. It must be numerically balanced
  2. Have a dramatic personality - in this case, this dice would travel and hobbles quite a bit before it decides to settle on a specific face
  3. Will roll even with the most minimal of effort
  4. Prints well with any standard FDM printer with easy to remove supports

Improve your tabletop gaming experience with a dice that understands that drama does require some level of anticipation :).

A video of the full explanation of the dice design can be viewed here: https://youtu.be/nQFpaxCI1CE

File Descriptions

The package contains the following files:

  • D20_v2_improved_30/120mm.stl - These are the latest, most improved version of the dice that rolls extremely well on both soft and hard surfaces. Recommended that you use this version.
  • D20_25/120mm.stl - Version 1.0 of the dice, which is more polygonal and improves upon similar commercial D20s in the market. Rolls better on soft surfaces. Print these if you like the more angular aesthetics of your dice.
  • D20-version1-source.fcstd - The FreeCAD 0.17 source file for version 1.0 of the dice.

The 25/30mm files are optimized for smaller dice scales (recommended scales being 30mm, 25mm and 21.5mm); while the 120mm ones are optimized for larger sizes and have a shallower indent for dice faces.

Update History

2017-09-14: Version 2.0: Now rolls on hard surfaces and bigger font!

After designing my ideal D6, I noticed a major flaw of my existing version 1.0 design: that it'll only roll well on softer surfaces but loses its dramatic personality on hard wood surfaces.

Learning my lesson with my newer D6 design, I've incorporated a spherical design to this new version and will now roll well on both soft and hard surfaces.

I've also used a bolder and larger font to improve the readability of the dice faces, whatever the scale you printed the dice. It also easier to paint over numbers to make stunning looking dice.

Notes:

Ideally should be printed with a perfectly leveled bed. But for the smaller 25mm dice I've factored in some first layer squish and some slack in the bridging.

Note that your top and bottom shell layer should be equal to ensure that the dice have a more or less even weight distribution. However with the 25mm version due to the fact that I've cut the groove deeper for the "1" face much deeper, it'd be lighter on the "1" face.

If you want a fair dice w/ equal weight distribution, scale down the 120mm version to the size that you wanted.

Date: 1905

Hi,
I was asked about blades with one piece.
This blade model is 177mm hight so you´ll have total diameter 40cm fan with centerpiece.
-Blade is solid piece with leg.
-Spinner has center pole and 1.2mm skin.
If you scale its wise to do scaling to all three parts. http://youtu.be/VmRh6whBj-c Now I have a some higher printer so this is getting exiting - I think I can reach between 60 and 70 cm fan with one print...

These are my first trial:
I sliced it vertical position with settings
0.4mm layer height, 2 perimeters and infill 10% (honeycomb 30°)
(Slicer1.0.0RC2)
To get more solid base feet for size 400 I used 50 solid layers.
For my speeds cooling fan is clearly needed with PLA.
There is clearly some difficulties with printing a sharp trailing edge so I used file and some water resistant sand paper there. If you want to make it perfect also some filler/paint might be necessary - with those treatments I think it not necessary to print this with high resolution in vertical position - that make things so much faster. I updated the spinner stl part. I got too much faults.
Also printed this with USB so some jaggered print). Hexagonal piece is solid with center holes etc are close to M5 size (without scaling of course). Some day I will try all the diameter 645 blades and parts in a one print. Scale 1.612 gives blade height 285mm and propeller diameter about 645mm. For size645 80 solid layers on bottom might be good. With Slic3r 1.0.0RC2 select part and settings in UI right upper corner - there is option for solid layer number for selected part so you can separate solid layer height in different parts. Scaling does not change the angle of attack so I suppose efficient RPM will go down. This design goal is to have slowest fan rotation, but might be wise to check the design some day - the blade root cord length seems quite narrow as a fan and might "leak" also the tip is not finalized... This might be that the design program was quite basic and restricted with propellers - It would be nice to have other efficient and quiet fan designs also.

description.text: An important part of electronics is recognizing functional blocks that form larger circuits.  This schematic is a drawing of a basic amplifier.  R1 and R2 form a resistive voltage divider to set the gain of the amplifier.  If you replace one of these with a potentiometer, you can adjust it.  This circuit will work with just about any op-amp.  EAGLE 4.16 format.

A few quick notes:  You can use this to build a simple headphone amplifier.  The greater the voltage you provide the amplifier with, the louder an output it can produce.  Common op-amps include the TL072, LM386, LM741 and TL082.  The goal is to have a bipolar supply.  If you use two 9 volt batteries, you can connect them to get +9v and -9v.  This allows the amplifier to go negative with it's output.

title: Printable drill jig for Rostock plywood parts

description.text:
This is a printable jig to make really precise top and bottom plywood frame parts for the Rostock delta robot 3D printer.
This jig is designed to work with plywood pieces of 350x300 mm. You may be able to drill both (top and bottom) at the same time.
12 mm (or maybe 9 mm) thick plywood is recommended to make the frame as strong as necessary. 6 mm thin plywood may be okay if your plywood is very good, and you are planning to make a back/side frame anyway, or if you are building a mini Rostock.

• Print the jig in PLA or ABS, it should fit on a 8x8 inch Prusa heated bed.

  • Align the drill jig with the longer edge of the plywood so that the middle hole is on the center line. Drill a 4mm hole in the middle and attach the jig with a M4 screw and nut.

  • Maybe use a small clamp to hold the jig in place. Drill two holes through the jig near the edge. Optionally put a M4 screw in the first hole before drilling the second one.

  • Repeat step 3 twice at 120 degree angles. If you draw a straight line through the middle hole, parallel to the first edge, then you can align the sides of the jig to this line.

  • With M4 screws in the new holes, mark the outside edge of the drill jig onto the plywood with a sharp pencil. Then remove the drill jig and cut away the 2 front corners of the plywood where the motor brackets will be attached. Use a precision circular table saw for best results, but a handheld jigsaw works okay too.

  • Attach a motor bracket to each pair of holes, then drill through its other two holes into the plywood. For the two front brackets it's okay to use only one of the inner holes because the other one overlaps with the heated bed.
    • Alternative: If you have a strong laser, make a DXF or EPS file of this design and laser cut from 6mm plywood. If 6mm plywood is not strong enough, maybe use two layers for the bottom frame. Upload your file to Thingiverse so that others can use it too.

description.text:
This is my remix of the fantastic "VEND - the totally printed candy dispenser" by ErikJDurwoodII. His design is a great conversation starter, and a fun way to show off your cool hobby.
I have made what I consider to be improvements on some of the parts provided in his original. In the instructions portion, I detail the changes and give information on parts that are interchangeable with the original. I have provided files for the parts that remain unchanged.
This machine works best with hard shiny candy like small gumballs, M&Ms and Reese's Pieces.
UPDATE 3/12/14: I replaced the NewFlap.stl with NewFlapCoinsRev1.stl and added NewFlapPlainRev1.stl
These flaps have a thicker hinge, but it still works with the other parts.
UPDATE 11/11/14: A
Due to a request from a user for a shorter body, I have uploaded a remixed version of KingRahl's shorter body.
I plan on a revision to the body, collar, and hatch parts to include a locking mechanism similar to my locking pencil box. Please check back in later!

I printed all parts on my Replicator Dual with .2mm layers at 8% infill at 90mm/s in PLA. None of the parts require support.
Here are the parts I changed:
NewBody.stl - I fixed the bridges that were not reaching the sides (see BadBridge.pdf). I made the slots for the hatch inserts bigger for a better fit. I made the lower hole for the clip penetrate all the way into the money compartment. I added the extruded 25 cent text above the coin slot.
This part is fully compatible with the original parts.
NewCoinFace.stl - I extruded the center portion of the arrows so the faces would be on the bed of the printer. I was not happy with the finish of the bridging on this very prominent face.
This part is fully compatible with the original parts.
NewDualDrum.stl - It seemed that lots of people wanted a drum that did not provide as much volume. I made a smaller drum that gives approximately 28 M&Ms for each quarter. Since it only took up a little room, I made it two sided. I revised the slots that the Pawl part clicks into for dual sided operation. I also switched the orientation of the handle to better show off the arrows on the coin face part. The original had a spacer that is no longer needed.
This part fits in the original, but should be used with the DualCoinCam and new locks.
NewDualCoinCam.stl - I mirrored the coin slot, so you only have to turn the handle 180 degrees to get candy. I made the space for the locks larger for the updated locks.
This part fits the original, but should be used with the DualDrum and new locks.
NewLocks.stl - I had problems with the original locks slipping past the opening, and then you had to disassemble the machine to fix it. The new parts more closely match the mechanics in the coin face, and have a ramp on the back side that lets you turn it back if it does slip.
These parts can only be used with the DualCoinCam.
NewClips.stl - I had a hard time getting the clips deep into the body, and they seemed to want to pop out once installed. I added the long handles to get them started, then you can push them in with a long screwdriver. I beefed up the clip and stretched it a bit, so it holds tight.
These parts are compatible with the original parts.
NewFlap.stl - I could not cut the right parts off the original part without breaking it, so I made it print with supports that you just break off. I made a place to put in 2 quarters during the print (pause it to insert them). They provide weight to the flap so the candy doesn't shoot out! The coins fit pretty tightly if they are new, but if you don't want them to spin, use a dab of super glue before you insert them.
Updated Rev1 parts are more durable, and I included a no coin version.
This part is compatible with the original parts.
All the remaining parts that begin with Vend are original parts included here for ease of download. No changes have been made.

title: Surround Print Cooler - 40x40 fan (for E3D type hotends)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
----------------------- 40 x 40 mm AIAL FAN version -----------------------

This "Remix" of my previous print coolers integrates some useful feedback I received from people who printed and used the old versions. Although these worked fine for me, I have to admit they were designed quite tight and some people had problems with the cooler duct touching the nozzle or they had trouble getting the BLTouch in.

THANKS to everyone who provided feedback on the design!

Following points are updated / changed:

  • The distance between the cooling duct and the heating block is now large enough to avoid touching in any situation. This also leaves more space for the heater cables.
  • The section diameter of the cooling duct is increased to minimize pressure loss
  • The mounting requires only screws for the fans. The two components (print cooler and radiator cooler) are now held together exclusively by dove-tail friction joints
  • Cleaner and improved overall geometry
  • Added double fan version for those who need more cooling power

The radius of the cooling pipe leaves enoguh space between the 3D printed part and the heating block. However, I recommend that you insulate your heating block with fireproof insulation (you can find it in any 3D printer store or online) for 3 reasons:

  • To avoid the pipe getting heat deformations
  • To avoid cooling down the hotend and destabilizing the temperature PID controller
  • To avoid heating up the cooling air

I hope that you will like and successfully use this cooler! Please provide feedback for potential improvements.

Acknowledgement:

  • Benjamin Grosjean / GrabCAD - 3D model of the fans (https://grabcad.com/library/fan-40-x-40-mm-1)

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15-0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

It will take ca. 35g filament.

If the friction in the dove-tail joints is not enough, increase the extrusion multiplier (to ca. 105%). If the dove-tail joints are too tight, try sanding them off a little to get the right fit.

The aluminium radiator has a diameter that can vary between 22 and 22.5 mm. I designed the radiator fan duct for 22mm, so for some of you, this might be too tight and lead to breaking the clips during mounting.

If the radiator fan duct clips are too tight, try heating them up a little before mounting, to avoid breaking them. Alternatively, you can use a rotary tool to grind them off until they fit.

1. Import one of the “Print_Cooler” .STP files (without holes) in your prefered CAD software.

  2. Estimate the center (O) of the main cooling duct torus.

  3. Move this point vertically at a certain distance H (default: 7mm) from the nozzle. This will be the point where the air jets will be aiming. Do not place it to close to the nozzle, else you risk cooling down and clogging the nozzle.

  4. In “front” or “right” view, draw a line from “O” to a point iside the cooling duct.

  5. Multiply this line in a circular pattern (16-30 elements should be fine).

  6. Adjust the lines in the area of the BLTouch bulge.

  7. Use the created lines as axes for pipes with D = 1.6-3 mm.

  8. Subtract those pipes from the imported “Print_Cooler” .STP geometry.

  9. Delete the pipes and lines to reveal the customized model.

The cooling assembly has 2 parts:

  1. Print cooler for 40x40 axial fans (I included a version with no holes too, if you want to change the hole pattern and orientation)
  2. Radiator fan holder, or radiator cooler for 30x30 axial fans

I designed them as two separate parts to be easier to mount and print without supports.

For the mounting, you will only need 4 or 6 M3 screws (for the fans). The length of those will depend on the depth of your fan, but generally, M3x15 - M3x25mm should work.

Assembly order:

  1. insulate your heating block
  2. clip in the radiator fan holder
  3. slide the print cooler from the bottom into the dove-tail slots of the radiator fan holder
  4. mount the axial fans with M3 screws (or similar)
  5. adjust your PID (if necessary)
  6. enjoy your improved cooling

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
There's a few good pill dispensers here already, but I wanted something to help me learn Fusion 360 so I decided to design my own. My criteria were that I wanted it to be easy to use and easy to refill; secure enough to safely store a week's worth of the various medications my doctors like me to take, easy to see the day names (without having to put on my glasses), and I wanted it to be reasonably pleasing to the eye.

I also wanted something easy to print that doesn't require any supports, or any non-printable parts.

After much trial and error, and quite a few variations, I'm finally happy with the result (and I have learned a lot about how to do stuff in Fusion 360!).

BAMBOO ZEN VASE

A Zen-style, decorative flower vase. The vase is built from two objects:

  • Bamboo rod
  • Vase (three different styles included)

Simply print one (or more) bamboo rods and put them into the vase(s). The bamboo rod can hold a flower or anything decorative.

PRINT SETTINGS:

  • Use a raft for the bamboo rod and print it upright
  • Use 0-5% infill
  • Wall thickness 0.8mm
  • Layer height: 0.3mm
  • Print speed: 65mm/s

The bamboo rod can be printed without any infill at all if you don't care about the inner bottom plate of the rod (which is not visible on the finished part). If you'd like a properly printed bottom plate inside the rod, you'll need to use some infill though (8-10% should be fine).

The vases can be printed without any supports, but the inner curve on the top of the vase is a bit difficult to print. Some loose and hanging strands may appear there when no supports are used.

If you prefer a perfect and tidy print, you should place some supports in the center of the vase. I included a support mesh that can be used with Cura and also tutorial pictures that show how to use this support mesh.

POST PRINTING:

Use some spray effect paint to achieve different looks, for example chrome effect, metal effect or granite effect spray.

I have the Creality CR10 S5 and TDH's EZABL (Automatic Bed Leveling) kit. I wanted a way to mount it to the frame with T-Nuts so I created this case. The original case has 4 holes but I couldn't find a good place to mount it. I have the Direct Wire version.

Per Tim's instructions, to remove the circuit board from the current case you need to heat up the bottom of the case with a heat gun until the hot glue softens and you can remove the circuit board. This worked fine for me and softened up the sides of the case too so I could sort of peel them down to get a better grip on the board. I assume no responsibility if you damage your circuit board doing this. Just don't over heat it and you should be good to go.
It's a tight fit for the board so I didn't even bother using hot glue to secure it in the new case and since it's mounted on the frame there is very little movement.

I made the inserts for the lid screws pretty big but the actual holes small so you should be able find 2 tiny screws to secure the lid. I actually used 2 small wood screws. There is plenty of room to drill them out bigger if need be.

All the wires exit around the lip of the case instead of holes on the side.

Just place it on the frame where you want it and secure it with T-Nuts. If you need T-Nuts you can get them from Amazon. I used the M5x8 but you probably could use longer one too.

description.text:
I made these buttons to work a bit better with the Pigrrl Zero Plus build but they could work for the regular build as well. The DPAD and buttons files both have four little indents on the bottom to correspond to the tactile buttons. I found that the soft tactile buttons from Adafruit have a pretty high travel length so the buttons would result in false presses. The indents solve this issue. I have used them a decent amount on my build with no issue but I am not guaranteeing they will work for everyone.

I also added little embossed arrows to the DPAD so it looks a bit fancier as well as making the A and B buttons concave and the X and Y buttons convex to mimic a SNES controller. I also put an L and R on the shoulder buttons also just to be fancy. I printed these in TPE with low infill to make them squishy but I am fairly confident hard plastics would work.

description.text:
I wanted to make a self feeding water dish for our new cats that could hold a large amount of water. All the others I found on here seemed to be built for 20oz or smaller bottles. I decided to make one that could attach to a 32oz or 64oz Gatorade bottle(they have the same threads). This was not the first version but it uses about half of the plastic the original did. It requires a build area of at least 175mm x 140mm, not huge, but not for smaller printers.

Also, for best feed rate I've found that I tighten the full bottle all the way on, flip it over, then unscrew it about 1/4 turn. The bubbles flow freely then. The 32oz bottle lasted about 2 days with two cats drinking from it. So far, I've been the only one to knock the 64oz bottle one over, the cats have yet to knock either one over.

12/06/2017
Just revamped the dish to address a few things. The one ending in ver2 is the newest at this point. It has a less pronounced lip and fewer sharp crevices, both are for easier cleaning, I found mold was able to grow in those hard to reach areas. Also, I beefed up the neck where the bottle attaches, broke one on the old model(it still functions, but just wanted to address it). Finally, it's a bit more low profile, which, as it turns out, uses only about 80% of the plastic that the old one did and thus prints in 80% of the time. Finally, I made the stabilizer bars a bit smaller, they work just as well and unlike the older model, I haven't had them warp during printing on my non-heated bed. Enjoy!!!
